commits.message:
Revert "No speedup in optimizing readbytes"

readbytes() already takes in a ByteBuffer, and ByteBuffer.get(byte[])
already uses native JVM memory copying.  So the advantage of using System.arraycopy bypassing ByteBuffer allocation and book-keeping is no more.

```java
// linux x86_64 generated source java.nio.HeapByteBuffer
public ByteBuffer get(byte[] dst, int offset, int length) {
    checkSession();
    Objects.checkFromIndexSize(offset, length, dst.length);
    int pos = position();
    if (length > limit() - pos)
        throw new BufferUnderflowException();
    System.arraycopy(hb, ix(pos), dst, offset, length);
    position(pos + length);
    return this;
}
```

The callers of readbytes() tend to already have a ByteBuffer at hand and perform stateful reads of objects, such as ByteUtils.readVarint() and headers. Non-emtpy headers tend to have varying sizes, so stateful reads by ByteBuffer is easier and is likely no worse than stateful reads in byte array.

